{"schema":"algviz/1","title":"Min-Heap Extract-Min (sift-down)","topic":"heaps-and-priority-queues","code":["public int Pop()                               // O(log n)","{","    int root = _h[0];","    int last = _h.Count - 1;","    _h[0] = _h[last];","    _h.RemoveAt(last);","    SiftDown(0);","    return root;","}","","private void SiftDown(int i)","{","    int n = _h.Count;","    while (true)","    {","        int l = 2*i+1, r = 2*i+2, smallest = i;","        if (l < n && _h[l] < _h[smallest]) smallest = l;","        if (r < n && _h[r] < _h[smallest]) smallest = r;","        if (smallest == i) break;","        (_h[i], _h[smallest]) = (_h[smallest], _h[i]);","        i = smallest;","    }","}"],"structures":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","label":"heap array (storage)"},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","label":"complete tree (view)"}},"frames":[{"line":1,"caption":"Start with the min-heap [2, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6, 4]. Pop extracts the minimum, which always sits at the root.","note":"A binary heap is a complete tree packed into an array with one invariant: every parent is <= its children (min-heap), so the smallest element is always at the root. Pop must return that root in O(1) and then restore the invariant with a single sift-down. The tree on screen mirrors the array: the children of index i are at 2i+1 and 2i+2.","vars":{"heap":"[2, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6, 4]","root (min)":2},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":2,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":4,"highlight":"filled"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":2,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":3,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":4,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"}]}}},{"line":3,"caption":"Save the root 2 — this is the minimum we will return.","note":"Pop always returns the root — for a min-heap that is the minimum, available in O(1) because the invariant parks the extreme element on top. But we cannot just delete the root: that would leave a hole at index 0 and two orphaned subtrees. The fix is to refill the hole with the ONLY node we are allowed to remove without reshaping the tree — the last leaf.","vars":{"heap":"[2, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6, 4]","root (min)":2,"root":2},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":2,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":4,"highlight":"filled"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":2,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"match"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":3,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":4,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"}]}}},{"line":4,"caption":"The last element is a[6]=4. It is the only leaf we can remove while keeping the tree complete.","note":"Why the LAST element fills the hole: a heap must stay a COMPLETE tree (every level full, last level filling left-to-right) so the array encoding stays gap-free. The last array slot is the only leaf whose removal preserves completeness. So we copy it to the root and drop the tail (_h.RemoveAt(last)). The tree shape is now valid again; only the value at the root is likely out of order, so one root-to-leaf sift-down repairs it.","vars":{"heap":"[2, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6, 4]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":2,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":4,"highlight":"active"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":2,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"active"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":3,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":4,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"active"}]}}},{"line":5,"caption":"Move 4 into the root and drop slot 6. The shape is valid again; only the root may be out of order.","note":"Why the LAST element fills the hole: a heap must stay a COMPLETE tree (every level full, last level filling left-to-right) so the array encoding stays gap-free. The last array slot is the only leaf whose removal preserves completeness. So we copy it to the root and drop the tail (_h.RemoveAt(last)). The tree shape is now valid again; only the value at the root is likely out of order, so one root-to-leaf sift-down repairs it.","vars":{"heap":"[4, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":4,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"active"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":3,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"muted"}]}}},{"line":18,"caption":"Compare a[0]=4 with its children; the smaller child is a[2]=3.","note":"Sift-down must compare the node with the SMALLER of its two children (min-heap) — comparing the wrong child is the classic heap bug. We read both children at 2i+1 and 2i+2, take whichever is smaller, and that is the only candidate that could legally sit above the other. A node with no children is a leaf and is automatically done.","vars":{"heap":"[4, 5, 3, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6,"i":0,"a[i]":4,"left a[2i+1]":"a[1]=5","right a[2i+2]":"a[2]=3","smaller child":"a[2]=3"},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":4,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"active"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"compared"},{"key":"t2","value":3,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"compared"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null}]}}},{"line":20,"caption":"4 > smaller child: swap down to index 2 and continue.","note":"The node is larger than its smaller child, so the invariant parent <= children is violated here. Swap them: the smaller child rises (it is <= everything below it on this path), and the demoted node continues from the child index. Each swap moves it one level down, and the tree height is floor(log2 n), so sift-down touches at most log n levels — that is why pop is O(log n), not O(n).","vars":{"heap":"[3, 5, 4, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6,"i":2,"a[i]":4,"left a[2i+1]":"a[1]=5","right a[2i+2]":"a[2]=3","smaller child":"a[2]=3"},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"swapped"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":3,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"swapped"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":4,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"active"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null}]}}},{"line":18,"caption":"Compare a[2]=4 with its children; the smaller child is a[2]=4.","note":"Sift-down must compare the node with the SMALLER of its two children (min-heap) — comparing the wrong child is the classic heap bug. We read both children at 2i+1 and 2i+2, take whichever is smaller, and that is the only candidate that could legally sit above the other. A node with no children is a leaf and is automatically done.","vars":{"heap":"[3, 5, 4, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6,"i":2,"a[i]":4,"left a[2i+1]":"a[5]=6","smaller child":"a[2]=4"},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":3,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":4,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"active"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null}]}}},{"line":19,"caption":"a[2]=4 is already <= both children — sift-down stops, heap restored.","note":"Sift-down stops the instant the node is <= both its children (smallest == i) or it reaches a leaf. Exactly one root-to-leaf path was touched and every other parent/child pair was already ordered, so the whole heap satisfies parent <= children again. The new root is the new minimum — peek it in O(1), and the next pop repeats this same O(log n) repair.","vars":{"heap":"[3, 5, 4, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6,"i":2,"a[i]":4,"left a[2i+1]":"a[5]=6","smaller child":"a[2]=4"},"result":null,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":3,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t2","value":4,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"match"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null}]}}},{"line":8,"caption":"Pop returns 2. The repaired heap is [3, 5, 4, 8, 7, 6] — the new minimum 3 is on top.","note":"One pop = O(1) read of the root + O(log n) sift-down along a single root-to-leaf path. That O(1) peek and O(log n) push/pop is exactly what a priority queue sells: repeatedly extracting the next smallest/largest powers heap-sort, k-way merge, Dijkstra, and \"next best\" greedy scheduling.","vars":{"heap":"[3, 5, 4, 8, 7, 6]","root (min)":2,"root":2,"last":6,"h[last]":4,"n":6,"i":2,"a[i]":4,"left a[2i+1]":"a[5]=6","smaller child":"a[2]=4","returned (min)":2,"new root (min)":3},"result":2,"states":{"arr":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c2","value":3,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c1","value":5,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c0","value":4,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c3","value":8,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c4","value":7,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c5","value":6,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"c6","value":"·"}],"range":null},"tree":{"type":"binaryTree","root":"t0","nodes":[{"key":"t0","value":3,"left":"t1","right":"t2","highlight":"match"},{"key":"t1","value":5,"left":"t3","right":"t4","highlight":"match"},{"key":"t2","value":4,"left":"t5","right":"t6","highlight":"match"},{"key":"t3","value":8,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"t4","value":7,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"t5","value":6,"left":null,"right":null,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"t6","value":"·","left":null,"right":null}]}}}],"complexity":"O(1)"}